			<div class='intro__prelude'>
				<p>The Women's National Basketball Association (WNBA) is only the most recent chapter of a history of women's basketball dating back to the 1890's. Building upon several movements and the gains of past leagues, the WNBA has fully established itself as the premier women's basketball league in the U.S. The league continues to build its fan base and work toward a self-sustaining model. For fans who started following the league more recently, like myself, I've put together a brief visual history of the WNBA.</p>

				<h2>1997 - 2000: Houston + Expansion</h2>
				<p>The WNBA had its inaugural season in 1997, starting with 8 teams and a season of 28 games. In the first few years, the Houston Comets dominated the league with the original Big 3 of Cynthia Cooper, Tina Thompson and Sheryl Swoopes. They won the first 4 WNBA titles, kicking off the league with a full-fledged dynasty. By the end of this era the league had grown to 16 teams and a 30 game schedule.</p>

				<h2>2001 - 2002: LA Sparks</h2>
				<p>Following the Houston Comets Dynasty was a formidable pair of seasons from the LA Sparks led by WNBA icon Lisa Leslie. </p>

				<h2>2003 - 2009: Detroit Shock + Team Movement</h2>
