			<h1>Appendix</h1>
        	<h2>Origins</h2>
			<p>The long <a href="https://www.wnba.com/news/history-of-womens-basketball/">history of women’s involvement in basketball</a> dates back to the origins of the sport itself. In 1892, in tandem with basketball’s invention, <a href="https://jwa.org/encyclopedia/article/berenson-senda">Senda Berenson</a> introduced the game to Smith College in Massachusetts. Slowly, intercollegiate competition grew in the West at Cal-Berkeley and Stanford, in the South at <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/43609682?seq=1">Bennett College</a> and Sophie Newcomb College, in the Northeast at Bryn Mawr and Vassar, and in the Midwest at the University of Nebraska and Kanasas State.</p>

			<p>Much of the early growth of the game also took place in high schools. Already in 1896, Chicago Austin High School and Oak Park played the <a href="https://womenshoopsblog.wordpress.com/womens-basketball-timeline-since-1891/">first high school game</a>. By 1910, the <a href="https://www.blackfives.org/december-is-black-womens-basketball-history-month/">New York Girls</a>, the first all-black, all-female high school team, was founded and won a state championship. In 1924 came another important basketball moment: the sport's first 100-point game. Except it wasn't just a 100-point game. It was a <a href="http://www.espn.com/espn/page2/story?page=list/060124">156 point outburst</a> by Marie Boyd in an overall demolition of 163-3. Absolutely merciless.</p>

			<h2>Industrial Teams &amp; Barnstorming</h2>
			<p>In the 1910's and 20's, quasi-professional industrial teams sponsored by corporations began to emerge. It was great publicity to have a winning team, and by 1923 there were enough teams to have a formal tournament culminating in the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edmonton_Grads#North_American_Underwood_Trophy">Underwood Trophy</a>. The Edmonton Grads (i.e. the Commercial Graduates) consistently dominated this league and all other competition. Between 1915 and 1940, the team went an astonishing 502-20, winning against men's teams, universities, industrial teams, and Olympic competition.</p>

			<p>In this era, overcoming both gender discrimination and racism, some of the earliest professional basketball clubs founded were the all-black <a href="https://originalpeople.org/top-25-african-americans-who-pioneered-the-integration-of-pro-basketball/">Chicago Romas</a> (1920) and <a href="https://www.blackfives.org/all-hail-the-philadelpha-tribune-girls-happy-birthday-ora-mae-washington/">Philadelphia Tribunes</a> (1931). The star players of each team, Ora Mae Washington and Isadore Channels, were excellent athletes who were also champion tennis players of the era. Notably, the Romas, who competed against men's and women's teams, didn't lose a single game during a six year span from 1939 to 1945.</p> 

			<p>Also founded in the 1930’s and 40’s, all-white barnstorming professional teams like the <a href="https://arktimes.com/news/cover-stories/2012/11/07/without-the-all-american-red-heads-there-would-be-no-wnba">All American Red Heads</a> (1936) and <a href="https://www.kuaf.com/post/womens-basketball-today-has-arkansas-connection#stream/0">Arkansas Travelers</a> (1949) played in arenas and literal barns across the country. They each played exclusively against men’s teams, beating them 70% to 80% of the time. The Travelers, led by early basketball icon <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hazel_Walker">Hazel Walker</a> would continue to compete through the 1960's.</p>

			<h2>Professional Leagues</h2>
			<p>It took the better part of a century though for the first professional league, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Women%27s_Professional_Basketball_League">Women's Professional Basketball League</a> (WBL), to form in 1978. While it only lasted through 1983 (unpaid salaries rightfully led to player protests and the league’s closure), it set the stage for professional leagues to follow in the U.S. It led to the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Women%27s_American_Basketball_Association">Women’s American Basketball Association</a> (WABA), which had on-and-off seasons between 1984 and 1995. Ultimately, interest in the sport led to the founding of the WNBA in 1996 and its first season in 1997. With it began the most recent and powerful chapter of professional women’s basketball in the United States.</p>
